+                1. Quantum computers use qubits that can exist in superposition states.
+                2. Google achieved quantum supremacy in 2019 with their Sycamore processor.
+                3. IBM plans to deliver 100,000-qubit systems by 2033.
+                4. Key applications include cryptography, drug discovery, and optimization.
+                5. Current challenges include error correction and maintaining coherence.
+                """,
+            var q when q.Contains("artificial intelligence") || q.Contains(" ai ") =>
+                """
+                1. Large language models have transformed NLP since GPT-3 in 2020.
+                2. AI agents with tool-use capabilities are a major research focus in 2025-2026.
+                3. Regulation frameworks are being adopted worldwide (EU AI Act, US executive orders).
+                4. Multimodal models now handle text, images, audio, and video.
+                5. Energy consumption of AI training remains a growing concern.
+                """,
+            _ =>
+                $"""
+                1. "{query}" is an active area of research.
+                2. Recent developments show significant progress in this field.
+                3. Multiple organizations are investing in related technologies.
+                4. Challenges remain around scalability and practical applications.
+                5. Expert consensus suggests continued growth over the next decade.
+                """
+        };
+    },
+    "search_web",
+    "Searches the web for information on a given query. Returns a list of relevant results.");
+
+var addNoteTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(
+    (string title, string content) =>
+    {
+        noteService.AddNote(title, content);
+        Console.WriteLine($"  [Note saved: \"{title}\"]");
+        return $"Note '{title}' saved successfully.";
+    },
+    "add_note",
+    "Saves a research note with a title and content for later reference.");
+
+var getNotesTool = AIFunctionFactory.Create(
+    () =>
+    {
+        var notes = noteService.GetNotes();
+        if (notes.Count == 0) return "No notes saved yet.";
+        return string.Join("\n\n", notes.Select(n => $"## {n.Title}\n{n.Content}"));
+    },
+    "get_notes",
+    "Retrieves all saved research notes.");
